{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_jig_ver01/data/sn85025570/00383348316/1930040901/0209.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nTHE REDWOOD GAZETTE\nPublished by the\nREDWOOD GAZETTE PUBLISHING CO n INC.\nRedwood Falls, Minn.\nW. E. BARNES, Pres.; B. E. MARSH, Vive Pres.;\nESTHER DAVIS STENSVAD, Secy, and Treas.\nB. E. Marsh and Esther Davis Stensvad, Editors\nB. E. Marsh, Business Manager\nFull Year In Advance $2.00\nCanada and Foreign Countries $2.50\nJL/ 5\nTO OUR jSn\nFILIATING MEMBER*\nWEDNESDAY, APRIL 9, 1930\nSurest Farm Relief\nANY farm relief worthy of the name must come\nfrom the farmer himself, in the opinion of agri\ncultural authorities, with governmental agencies\nranking a poor second-best in any real improvement\nof the farm situation. Increased efficiency on the part\nof the farmer himself will go furthest towards im\nproving rural conditions.\nThere are certain basic principles which must be\nfollowed if a farmer is to succeed as he should. The\nfirst of these is that a great share of the products\nused by the farm family should be produced at home;\nsecond, that the farm land should not be robbed year\nafter year, but should be kept up and improved; and\nthird, that the farmer should keep livestock and grow\nmore than one cash crop.\nFailure to realize to the fullest upon certain in\nherent advantages of farm life is depriving many\nfarmers of a large share of the ready cash which their\nfellow farmers are securing each Profits from\nthe farm poultry flock is one of these things, to cite\nan outstanding example.\nFarmers in some sections of the country are mak\ning each hen on the farm pay a net profit of between\n$1.50 and $2.50 a year. Many farmers, however, over\nlook this valuable source of income, leaving it to\ntheir wives as a \u201cpin money\u201d proposition. Improve\nment of farm poultry stock, principally by taking ad\nvantage of a greatly improved hatchery product, has\nmade possible large profits from poultry activities in\nrecent years.\nSticking To The Job\nWERE the average youngster inducted into a new\njob and positively assured that he must remain\nwith the same institution for 70 years, he\nwould probably look upon the prospect with horror.\nBut August C. Kessinger of Rome, N. Y., has vol\nuntarily stuck to the Sentinel that long, thereby estab-\nlishing a record that is perhaps unique in the annuals\nof newspaperdom. Eight years as an employee and\nsixty-two years as publisher summarizes his connec\ntion with that newspaper.\nDuring his regime the Sentinel has chronicled the\nevents of the Civil War, the Spanish-American War\nand the World War, as well as many stirring happen\nings in between and since. It has seen its home town\ngrow into a thriving manufacturing city and has\ndoubtless contributed more to the advancement of its\ncommunity than any other agency.\nYet there are probably a good many readers of the\nSentinel who feel that they could give Mr. Kessinger\nsome valuable advice on how to run his paper.\nWalter Eckersall\nFOLLOWERS of sports were saddened recently by\nthe sudden death of Walter H. Eckersall, one of\nthe greatest footfall stars of all time, also fam\nous sport writer and referee. His life was snuffed out\nby a heart attack at the age of forty-two.\nEckersall attained the pinnacle of gridiron fame\nas end and quarterback of the University of Chicago\nteam between 1903 and 1906, being chosen as a mem\nber of Walter Camp\u2019s mythical All-Americans in three\nsuccessive years. During his football days, Eckersall\u2019s\nweight ranged from only about 135 to 145 pounds, yet\nsuch was his speed, skill and audacity that he mowed\ndown heavyweight rivals who crossed his path.\nBy the younger generation of sport fans he was\nwidely known and acclaimed as a football writer and\nreferee of the highest rank. His contributions to the\nsporting page will be sadly missed by his admiring\nfollowers.\nEckeralPs early death will again revive the argu\nment as to whether too strenous athletics during youth\nmay not entail serious physical penalties of evidence\nto indicate that this is so, but the ambitious college\nathlete will hardly modify his exertions on that ac\ncount.\nWhen the glory of alma mater is at stake, all else\nis secondary.\nThe New Planet\nFOR years astronomers have searched the heavens\nfor a ninth planet, which mathematical calcula\ntions led them to believe existed beyond Neptune,\nassistant. Clyde Tombaughudy.ica;;;;; ;;risfl :ho mrl\nIt remained for a young American observatory assist\nant, Clyde Tombaugh. 23 years old. to find it. It was\nf.ot discovered directly through a telescope, but as a\nfaint spot of light on a photographic plate, and later\nverified as the long-sought body.\nIt may be unknown to many that this is the third\nplanet of our solar system to be discovered by man\nduring the last 150 years. hile the nearer planets\nwere known to the ancients, Uranus was not discover\ned until 1781, nor Neptune until 1846. The newly\nfound planet has not yet been named, nor has its size\nbeen determined.\nIts distance from the sun is thought to be between\nthree and four billion miles, while the earth is a little\niH O\no*o\no*o\nTHE REDWOOD GAZETTE, REDWOOD FALLS, MINN.\nless than 93 million miles from our central luminary.\nSo, while it is interesting to know that we have an\nadditional member of our solar system, its presence\nwill have little effect upon practical affairs.\nA few days after the discovery of the ninth planet\nj was announced, an Italian amateur astronomer claim\ned that he had found four new planets, making 12 in\nall, but so far his claim has not been verified by any\nrecognized authorities.\no*o\nThe Business Outlook\nI\nEVER since the stock market crash last fall many\nconflicting opinions have been expressed concern\ning the business outlook for 1930. There is no\ni denying the fact that there has been a slowing down\nin certain lines, but the views of leading industrialists\nand business men appear quite optomistic with the ad\nvent of Spring.\nThere is no doubt that the concerted effort of\nthese leaders to maintain high levels of production and\ndistribution is having a wholesome effect. Besides,\nlarge expenditures for permanent improvements by\nFederal, state and local authorities are getting under\nway, while billions are involved in expansion pro\ngrams of railroads, utilities and other basic industries.\nAn especially favorable trend is seen in the di\nrection of home building and home improvement, con\ncerning which a significant statement was made last\nI week after a nation-wide survey by Altorfer Bros.,\nmakers of Spinner washers, who said \u201cHome construc\ntion is up 425 per cent since 1920, and wired homes\nhave doubled in the intervening ten years. Various\nleading electrical home equipment distributors through\nout the United States reveal comprehensive plans to\nbuild new business during the year. There need be no\napprehension; indeed, there can be only optimism re\ngarding 1930.\u201d\nEncouraging reports have been forthcoming from\nmany other sources, so it appears that the temporary\ndepression may soon be ended. Incidentally, the pass\nage of the pending tariff bill should have a salutary\neffect upon the business situation, through relieving\nthe feeling of uncertainty which now exists in several\nimportant industries.\nShifting The Gears\nReform, like charity, should begin at home.\nO\nSo far, the Muscle Shoals agitation has been much\nado about doing nothing.\n<l*o\nMahatma Gandhi is encouraging the scofflaws of\nIndia to manufacture bootleg salt.\nThe expression \u201ceverything is jake\u201d doesn\u2019t apply\nafter imbibing a few jake cocktails.\nH. G. Wells says \u201cscrap the nations\u201d to prevent\nwar. But that would bring on the bigvgest scrap of all.\nJews and Arabs are squabbling about that wailing\nwall again. It seems that they will never get caught\nup with their wailing.\nA scientist thinks sleep is a form of intoxication.\nAnd woe unto the married man who talks loosely\nwhile under the influence.\nAn inquiring reporter asks: \u201cWhat kind of a hus\nband does a wife miss the most?\u201d The little fellows\nare more difficult targets.\n\u201cThe Silent Women of America\u201d is the name of\na new national organization. Strangely enoigh, it is\nnot composed of deaf-mutes.\nThat Wisconsin man who was fined for petting his\nown wife in public should have known that such un\nconventional conduct would not be tolerated.\nO O\nAnd speaking of names again, a John D. Rock\nfeller was sentenced to a penitentiary term of seven\nto ten years for robbery at Marquette, Mich.\nAn explorer declares that Commonwealth Bay, An-\ntarctica, is the windiest place in the world. But he\nprobably never visited the United States Senate cham\nber.\nA novelist makes the hero say: \u201cAs I gaze upon\nyour face, time stands still.\u201d And the heroine pro\nbably wondered whether he meant that her face would\nstop a clock.\nA Danish critic declares that movies are design\ned for the entertainment of nit-wits. Anyway, it\u2019s\nevident that either the movies or the critics are rot\nten in Denmark.\nPerhaps there isn\u2019t much in a name, but it must\nbe disconcerting to nervous persons to contemplate the\nsign on a hearse seen at New Carlisle, O. It reads,\n\u201cDoom Bros., Undertakers.\u2019\u2019\nNew York newspaper was sued for printing pic\ntures of a gorilla and a professional wrestler to\ngether. The gorilla might have a good case against\nboth newspaper and wrestler.\nAn Alabama railroad man declared he was \u201cready,\nwilling and anxious for a reconcilation\u201d after his wife\nhad sued for divorce seven times. But maybe he was\nmerely trying to dodge the alimony.\nPunch\u2019s famous advice to those about to get mar\nried, contained in the one word, \u201cDon\u2019t,\u201d is paraphras\ned by that given by an Atlanta newspaper to a sub\nscriber who asked: \u201cIt is unlucky to postpone a wed\nding?\u201d The answer was: \u201cNot if you keep on doing\nit.\u201d\nShort story: Margaret Black of Chicago passed\na bad check for ten dollars on James Dale, who had\nher arrested. After hearing the girl\u2019s hard luck tale,\nthe judge dismissed the case. Court spectators took\nup a collection to reimburse Dale. Dale presented the\nmoney to Margaret Black.\nAfter divorcing her husband, Mrs. Mary Draft of\nPhiladelphia consented to allow him to remain in their\njointly owned home as a boarder. It didn\u2019t work, how\never, as she later told the judge: \u201cI had to put him\nout because he began beating me just as though we\nwere married.\u201d\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\no*o\nSLATS\u2019 DIARY\nBY ROSS FARQUHAR\ndr. Doan at the hard\nted to sell me a\nBisickle today, he\noffered 1 to me\nfor a down and\na a week. They\nwas onley 1 thing\nwitch kep me\nfrum hying the bi\nsickle frum him\nand that was be\ncuz I diddent have\nthe down in\ncash right at this\npresent time now.\nSaterday\u2014W ile\nwe was out ride\ning in the 2nd\nhanded ford to\nnite pa was drive-\nFriday\u2014well IV\nwear sore wan\nJjflt 'vHE\ning and we hap-\npened to hit a cat.\nPa sed Thank Hevan for that and ma\nsed to him How cum you sed that\nand pa sed thank hevan it didn\u2019t get\nacrost our path witch makes you un\nlucky.\nSunday\u2014l herd sum queer noises\nlast nite after I had went to bed so\nI got up out of bed and tuk thirty\n5 c out my pockit and put it in my\nstocken and throwed it over in the\ncorner, and than I layed a wake the\nrest of the nite a watching it. Rock\nafellow and Ford and me loses lots\nof sleep. _\nMunday\u2014Today in the histry class\nthe teecher ast Jake what was a Cen\ntennial. she kinda cot him napping\nand he looked at her a secont and\nthen a sed A centennial is a wirm\nwith about a 1000 laigs.\nTuesday\u2014well ma dm? I and pa to\na nother Recital tonite where they\nwas doing a lot of singing and play\ning and ect. 1 lady sung a cupple\nsongs in sopranna and then 1 lady\nsung a cupple in French. Ma sed\nthey sung like birds and pa sed he\nwood of like to had a shotgun. I\ngess him and I will never lern to\nappreshiate true Art. Musiccle art,\nyre mean.\nWensday\u2014Tonite at the party af\nter they had served the ice cream and\ncake a good menny of the men left\nand went home. I sed to Jane Sup\npose all the gentlemens wood leave\nthe party and she replyed and sed\nWell even if they did we wood have\nyou left and a few uthers. I had a\nbi\u00bbj noshun to get sore but what\ngood wood it do if I had of.\nThirsday\u2014l of pa\u2019s cuzzens stop\nped here today for a cupple hours\nand he tawked all the time about his\nparents and how wonderful they was.\nAfter he had went pa sed He is such\na big lire mebby he never had no\nparents a tall. For all pa new about\nhim.\nGazette Want Ads Get Results.\nOpposite\nNew\nDream\nTheatre\nYour National Tea Store will serve you Quality Merchandise at low prices every day in\nthe week. Shop the National Tea Way for satisfaction in food stuffs and economy.\nSpecial prices for Friday, Saturday and Monday, April 11, 12, 14.\nV CIGARETTES, 2 Pkgs 2SC J\nMacaroni 1 CANDY BARS and GUM, 3 for 10c I Mayon\na\"d MARSHMALLOWS, Bulk, Lb. 19c nai\u00dfe\nSpaghetti SHREDDED WHEAT, Pkg 10c H l\nPkgs. FLOUR, Whole Wheat, 5 Lb. Bag -30 c 8 Z\nBLACKBERRIES, No. 10 Can 72c Jar\nlife PEACHES, Fey. Dried, Lb 23c 17c\nAPRICOTS, Fcq. Dried, Lb 33c S\nBread\nNational\nMaid\nIVi Lb.\nLoaf\n9c\nFruits and Vegetables\n\u201cAPPLES in HEADLETTUCE m\n3 Lbs 1\u00bbC 2 for UfC j\nBANANAS\n3 Lbs LOC i I\n\n_\nUSE\u2014THE\u2014GAZETTE\u2014WANT\nMake it a point to see us first\nwhen in need of a loan on\nyour City or Farm\nProperty.\nState Bank Trust Co.\nR. A. Cooper, Vice President\nA. F. Hassenstab, Cashier\nj\nj^aOAIJTY^OCKkS^^\nPRUNES, Fey. Large, Lb 19c\nMATCHES, Carton of 6 19c\nMILK, Hazel, 3 Tall Cans\nMolasses, Aunt Dinah, No. 2V2 Can 19c\nOIL MAZOLA, Qt. Can -45 c\nPEANUT BUTTER, Bulk, Lb. 19c\nSALT, Hazel lodized, Pkg 10c\nOXYDOL, 23 oz. Pkg.\nKITCHEN KLENZER, 3 Cans 14c\nHighest Market Price paid for Eggs\u2014Cash or Trade.\n\u201cMy Dad's Smart*\u2019...\nStarted a Bank Account for me. Says when I\nfinish with prep school, there\u2019ll be money enough\nin it to put me through college. Great, eh?\nUrge your Dad to start an Education Savings\nAccount for you.\nof Redwood Falls\nA. C. Burmeister, President\nWEDNESEDAY, APRIL 9, 1930 \\J'\nv,\nOFFICERS\nE. W. Whiting, Asst. Cashier\nG. R. Engeman, Asst. Cashier\n23c\nA. N.\nManning,\nManager\nPhone 378\nRedwood Falls\nCoffee\nSpecial\nBlend\n3\nPounds\n72c\nf\nP\n.Vjt","height":"25839","width":"19626"}}
